---
/**
 * TigerBalmBlock — About Tiger Balm.
 *
 * Editorial card about the menthol + camphor balm invented in 1870s
 * Rangoon by the Aw family. Still made, still works, still comes in that
 * same small hexagonal jar with the tiger on the label. Cultural icon.
 */
---

<section class="mt-10 mb-8" id="tiger-balm">
  <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-3">
    <div class="h-px flex-1 bg-rule/40"></div>
    <h2 class="font-mono text-[0.58rem] tracking-[0.22em] uppercase text-ink-soft/60">
      About &middot; <span class="text-warm">Tiger Balm</span>
    </h2>
    <div class="h-px flex-1 bg-rule/40"></div>
  </div>

  <article
    class="relative rounded-xl border-2 border-ink/80 overflow-hidden"
    style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #b91c1c 0%, #991b1b 50%, #7f1d1d 100%);"
  >
    <!-- Corner blocks -->
    <span class="absolute top-0 left-0 w-3 h-3 bg-yellow-400" aria-hidden="true"></span>
    <span class="absolute top-0 right-0 w-3 h-3 bg-paper" aria-hidden="true"></span>
    <span class="absolute bottom-0 left-0 w-3 h-3 bg-paper" aria-hidden="true"></span>
    <span class="absolute bottom-0 right-0 w-3 h-3 bg-yellow-400" aria-hidden="true"></span>

    <div class="p-5 md:p-7 text-paper">
      <p class="font-mono text-[0.52rem] tracking-[0.22em] uppercase text-yellow-400 mb-1">
        1870 · Rangoon · still working
      </p>
      <h3 class="font-heading text-[2rem] md:text-[2.4rem] leading-none mb-3">
        Tiger Balm
      </h3>
      <p class="font-serif italic text-[0.95rem] leading-snug mb-3 max-w-[36rem]">
        Camphor, menthol, cajuput, clove, mint. A recipe from Rangoon’s
        herbalist Aw Chu Kin, carried to Singapore by his sons in the 1920s,
        and never substantially changed since. Red jar warms, white jar is
        milder.
      </p>
      <p class="text-[0.9rem] leading-relaxed text-paper/90 max-w-[36rem] mb-3">
        Works on sore muscles, headaches, mosquito bites, bad posture, the
        urge to sit still. It’s not medicine in the FDA sense — it’s ritual.
        The same small hex jar your grandmother had is the same one in a
        Bangkok pharmacy today. There is a tiger on it because the Aw family
        name means “tiger” in Hokkien.
      </p>
      <!-- Per 2026-04-17 direction, blocks don't link off. These bullets
           now summarize the corners of the brand inline instead. -->
      <div class="grid grid-cols-3 gap-2 mt-4">
        <div class="p-2 rounded-sm border border-yellow-400/30 bg-black/15 text-center">
          <p class="font-mono text-[0.42rem] tracking-[0.18em] uppercase text-yellow-400/70">founded</p>
          <p class="font-mono text-[0.82rem] font-bold">1870</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-2 rounded-sm border border-yellow-400/30 bg-black/15 text-center">
          <p class="font-mono text-[0.42rem] tracking-[0.18em] uppercase text-yellow-400/70">jar shape</p>
          <p class="font-mono text-[0.82rem] font-bold">hexagonal</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-2 rounded-sm border border-yellow-400/30 bg-black/15 text-center">
          <p class="font-mono text-[0.42rem] tracking-[0.18em] uppercase text-yellow-400/70">sold in</p>
          <p class="font-mono text-[0.82rem] font-bold">100+ countries</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>
</section>
